# Chapter 10 — The full roster

Ten chapters of Instruments closes on the whole picture — what fits where in a full orchestra or ensemble, and how the roster shapes what the music can do.

An orchestra isn't a big band with more instruments — it's a specific balance of families that took centuries to work out. When you look at the roster you see the layers of what was learned.

## The four families

```scheme
(define orchestra-families
  '((strings      violin viola cello bass)
    (woodwinds    flute oboe clarinet bassoon)
    (brass        horn trumpet trombone tuba)
    (percussion   timpani snare cymbal xylophone)))

(for-each (lambda (f) (display f) (newline)) orchestra-families)
```

Output:

```
(strings violin viola cello bass)
(woodwinds flute oboe clarinet bassoon)
(brass horn trumpet trombone tuba)
(percussion timpani snare cymbal xylophone)
```

Four families, four roles. Strings are the ground; woodwinds color; brass declares; percussion punctuates.

## A section-by-section census

```scheme
(define orchestra-census
  '((first-violins   16)
    (second-violins  14)
    (violas          12)
    (cellos          10)
    (double-basses    8)
    (flutes           3)
    (oboes            3)
    (clarinets        3)
    (bassoons         3)
    (horns            4)
    (trumpets         3)
    (trombones        3)
    (tuba             1)
    (timpani          1)
    (percussion       3)))

(display (apply + (map cadr orchestra-census))) (newline)
```

Output:

```
87
```

87 players in a symphony orchestra. That's the roster.

## World-music equivalents

Other traditions have their own rosters.

```scheme
(define gamelan
  '(bonang saron gender kendang gong-ageng))

(define carnatic-ensemble
  '(vocalist violin mridangam tanpura ghatam))

(define jazz-quartet
  '(saxophone piano bass drums))

(display gamelan) (newline)
(display carnatic-ensemble) (newline)
(display jazz-quartet) (newline)
```

Output:

```
(bonang saron gender kendang gong-ageng)
(vocalist violin mridangam tanpura ghatam)
(saxophone piano bass drums)
```

Three ensembles, three complete musical languages. Each has its own balance.

## The seating chart

```scheme
(define seating
  '((front-left    first-violins)
    (front-right   second-violins)
    (middle-left   violas)
    (middle-right  cellos)
    (back-left     woodwinds)
    (back-center   brass)
    (back-right    percussion-and-basses)))

(for-each (lambda (p) (display p) (newline)) seating)
```

Output:

```
(front-left first-violins)
(front-right second-violins)
(middle-left violas)
(middle-right cellos)
(back-left woodwinds)
(back-center brass)
(back-right percussion-and-basses)
```

Softer instruments up front, louder ones behind. Physics of sound = seating chart.

## The book closing shape

```scheme
(define instruments-vocabulary
  '((the-roster              chapter-1)
    (piano                   chapter-2)
    (strings                 chapter-3)
    (percussion              chapter-4)
    (japanese-bamboo-flute   chapter-5)
    (brass                   chapter-6)
    (african-drums           chapter-7)
    (indian-tabla            chapter-8)
    (strings-ensemble        chapter-9)
    (the-full-roster         chapter-10)))

(for-each (lambda (p) (display p) (newline)) instruments-vocabulary)
```

Output:

```
(the-roster chapter-1)
(piano chapter-2)
(strings chapter-3)
(percussion chapter-4)
(japanese-bamboo-flute chapter-5)
(brass chapter-6)
(african-drums chapter-7)
(indian-tabla chapter-8)
(strings-ensemble chapter-9)
(the-full-roster chapter-10)
```

Ten chapters. Fifteen-plus instruments. One vocabulary for making sound.

## What you know now

- Orchestra = four families, ~87 players, balanced sections.
- World music has parallel rosters: gamelan, carnatic, jazz.
- Seating maps to acoustic physics: softer forward, louder back.
- The book's whole point is *know what instrument goes where.*

## Try before you turn the page

```scheme
(display '(orchestra strings woodwinds brass percussion)) (newline)
```

You've walked the Book of Instruments.

